{{Infobox building | name = Biesdorf Palace | native_name = Schloss Biesdorf | former_names = | alternate_names = | image = File:Schloss Biesdorf 2016.jpg | alt = | caption = Biesdorf Palace, 2016 | map_type = | map_alt = | map_caption = | altitude = | building_type = [[Palace]] | architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] | structural_system = | cost = | client = | owner = | current_tenants = | landlord = | location = | address = | location_town = [[Berlin]] | location_country = [[Germany]] | coordinates = {{coord|52.5098|13.5577|type:landmark_region:DE|display=inline,title}} | start_date = 1868 | completion_date = | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | height = | floor_count = | floor_area = | main_contractor = | architect = [[Heino Schmieden]], [[Martin Gropius]] | architecture_firm = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | awards = | url = | references = }}
The '''Biesdorf Palace''' ({{lang-de|Schloss Biesdorf}}) is a [[Neoclassical Architecture|Neoclassical]]-style building in [[Marzahn-Hellersdorf]], [[Berlin]]. Constructed in 1868, [[Werner von Siemens]] acquired the palace in 1887. However, in 1889 he handed the building over to his son, [[Georg Wilhelm von Siemens]]. Damaged in [[World War II]], the building was reconstructed on the basis of its original appearance, with the work being completed in 2016.
==Bibliography== *Josef Batzhuber. "Schloss und Park Biesdorf, Stadtbezirk Marzahn-Hellersdorf", in ''Bund Heimat und Umwelt in Deutschland: Weißbuch der historischen Gärten und Parks in den neuen Bundesländern''. Bonn: 2005. pp. 29–31.{{ISBN|3-925374-69-8}}
